=== World War I ===
On 11 October 1914, Marie and Ferdinand were acclaimed as king and queen in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]].{{sfn|Marie 1991, Vol 2|pp=409<U+2013>12}} Princess Anne Marie Callimachi, a close friend of Marie's, wrote that "as Crown Princess, [Marie] had been popular; as queen, she was more loved".{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=180}} Marie maintained a certain influence on her husband and the entire court, leading historian A. L. Easterman to write that "it was not [Ferdinand], but Marie who ruled in Romania".{{sfn|Easterman|1942|pp=38<U+2013>42}} At the time of Ferdinand's ascension, the government was led by the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|liberal]] prime minister [[Ion I. C. Br<U+0103>tianu]]. Ferdinand and Marie jointly decided to not make many changes in court and let people accept the transition from one regime to another, rather than force them. Thus, many of Carol and Elisabeth's servants were kept in place, even the ones who were not particularly liked.{{sfn|Marie 1991, Vol 3|p=13}} With Br<U+0103>tianu's help, Marie began pressuring Ferdinand into entering the war; concurrently, she contacted various reigning relatives in Europe and bargained for the best terms for Romania, in case the country would enter the war.<ref name="odnb" /> Marie favoured an alliance with the [[Triple Entente]] (Russia, France and Britain), partly because of her British ancestry. Neutrality was not without perils, and entering the war with the Entente meant that Romania would act as Russia's "buffer" against possible attacks.{{sfn|Elsberry|1972|p=104}}

[[File:1917 - Regina Maria pe timpul vizitei <U+00EE>ntr-un spital <U+00EE>n anul 1917.jpg|thumb|left|Marie visiting a military hospital, 1917]]

Eventually, Marie demanded of Ferdinand in no uncertain terms that he enter the war, leading the French minister to Romania, Auguste F<U+00E9>lix de Beaupoil, Count of Saint-Aulaire, to remark that Marie was twice an ally to the French: once by birth and once by heart.{{sfn|Saint-Aulaire|1953|p=322}} Ferdinand gave in to Marie's pleas, and he signed a treaty with the Entente on 17 August 1916. On 27 August, Romania formally declared war on Austria-Hungary.{{sfn|Giurescu|1972|p=300}} Saint-Aulaire wrote that Marie "embraced war as another might embrace religion".{{sfn|Saint-Aulaire|1953|p=399}} After informing their children that their country had entered the war, Ferdinand and Marie dismissed their German servants, who could only remain in their service as "war prisoners" of sorts.<ref>Marie's journal, 27 August 1914, quoted in {{harvnb|Marie 1991, Vol 3|p=69}}.</ref> Early on during the war, Marie was involved in aiding the [[Romanian Red Cross]] and visited hospitals daily.{{sfn|Gauthier|2010|pp=190<U+2013>91}} During the first month of war, Romania fought no less than nine battles, some on Romanian soil, such as the [[Battle of Turtucaia]].{{sfn|Giurescu|1972|pp=300<U+2013>1}}

On 2 November 1916, Marie's youngest son, Prince Mircea, who had been sick with [[typhoid fever]], died at [[Buftea]]. Marie was distraught and wrote in her journal "can anything ever be the same?".<ref>Marie's journal, 10 November 1916, quoted in {{harvnb|Marie 1991, Vol 3|p=97}}</ref> After [[Battle of Bucharest|Bucharest fell]] to Austrian troops, the royal court was transferred to [[Ia<U+0219>i]], capital of the [[Moldavia]] region, in December 1916.<ref name="odnb" /> There, she continued to act as a nurse in military hospitals. Daily, Marie would dress as a nurse and go to [[Ia<U+0219>i railway station|the train station]], where she would receive more injured soldiers; then she would transport them to hospital.{{sfn|Saint-Aulaire|1953|p=360}}

[[File:1dec1918.jpg|thumb|right|The assembly at Alba Iulia, 1918]]

After the conclusion of the [[Russian Revolution]] in early November 1917 and the victory of the [[Bolshevik]]s, Romania became, in the words of diplomat Frank Rattigan, "an island surrounded on all sides by the enemy, with no hope of assistance from the Allies".{{sfn|Rattigan|1924|pp=194<U+2013>95}} Soon afterwards, Ferdinand signed the [[Truce of Foc<U+0219>ani|Treaty of Foc<U+0219>ani]], on 9 December 1917.{{sfn|Giurescu|1972|p=307}} Marie considered the treaty perilous, while Br<U+0103>tianu and <U+0218>tirbey believed it was a necessary measure for obtaining more time. Later turns of events would prove Marie to have assumed correctly.{{sfn|Gauthier|2010|p=215}} In 1918, Marie vehemently opposed the signing of the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|Treaty of Bucharest]], giving rise to her description as "truly the only man in Romania".{{sfn|Gauthier|2010|p=216}} The [[Armistice with Germany]] (11 November 1918) put an end to fighting in Europe and, thus, to the war.

In the tenth century, the [[Principality of Hungary]] had begun conquering Transylvania, which Hungarians had fully occupied by around 1200.{{sfn|Horedt|1958|pp=117<U+2013>23}} The idea of a "[[Greater Romania]]" had existed in the minds of Romanians in Transylvania for some time{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=203}} and Br<U+0103>tianu had actively supported the concept before the war.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=207}} In 1918, both [[Bessarabia]] and [[Bukovina]] voted for union with Romania. An assembly took place in the ancient city of [[Alba Iulia]] on 1 December 1918, where [[Vasile Goldi<U+0219>]] read the resolution for the [[Union of Transylvania with Romania|union of Transylvania]] with the [[Romanian Old Kingdom|Old Kingdom]]. This document, supported by Romanian as well as [[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxon]] deputies,{{sfn|Hupchik|1995|p=83}} established a ''High National Romanian Council'' ({{lang-ro|Marele Sfat Na<U+021B>ional Rom<U+00E2>n}}) for the province's temporary administration.{{sfn|Giurescu|1972|pp=311<U+2013>12}} Marie wrote, "the dream of ''Rom<U+00E2>nia Mare'' seems to be becoming a reality&nbsp;... it is all so incredible that I hardly dare believe it."{{sfn|Aronson|1973|p=237}} After the assembly, Ferdinand and Marie returned to Bucharest, where they were met by general mirth: "a day of 'wild, delirious enthusiasm', with the bands crashing and the troops marching and the people cheering".{{sfn|Aronson|1973|p=237}} Allied troops took part in the celebration and Marie was elated to see the Entente on Romanian soil for the first time.{{sfn|Marie 1991, Vol 3|pp=492<U+2013>93}}

=== Paris Peace Conference ===
{{Quote box
 | quote  = She is magnificent and we have, against all protocol, shouted our admiration. The day remained grey, but Queen Marie carried her light within her.
 | source = <U+2014> ''[[Le Matin (France)|Le Matin]]'', a French newspaper<ref name="mtn">{{cite news | title=Ainsi Parla la Reine de Roumanie | work=Le Matin | date=6 March 1919 | accessdate=28 November 2013 | author=Colette | location=Paris | p=1}}</ref>
 | width  = 25em
 | align  =right
}}
Because Ferdinand had refused to sign the Treaty of Bucharest and because Romania had been hostile towards the Central Powers until the end of the war, its place among the winning countries during the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] was guaranteed. The official delegation was led by Br<U+0103>tianu, who had just begun his third term as Prime Minister.{{sfn|Botoran|Moisuc|1983|pp=328<U+2013>36}} Br<U+0103>tianu's rigidity, combined with French Prime Minister [[Georges Clemenceau]]'s reluctance to overlook Ferdinand's acceptance of the Treaty of Bucharest led to open conflict and the Romanian delegation left Paris, much to the dismay of the "[[The Big Four (World War I)|Big Four]]". Hoping to resolve the situation, Saint-Aulaire suggested that Marie should be sent to the conference instead. The Queen was delighted at the prospect.{{sfn|Ciubotaru|2011|p=xxiv}}

[[File:La reine de Roumanie <U+00E0> Paris, dans la cour de l'H<U+00F4>tel Ritz avec ses deux filles 1919, Meurisse.jpg|thumb|left|Marie with her two eldest daughters in Paris, 1919]]

Marie arrived in Paris on 6 March 1919.<ref name="mtn" /> She was immediately popular with the French people, due to her boldness during the War.<ref>[[Jean Jules Henri Mordacq|General Mordacq]], apud {{harvnb|Gauthier|2010|p=238}}.</ref> Upon meeting Marie, Clemenceau abruptly told her, "I don't like your Prime Minister", to which she replied, "Perhaps then you'll find me more agreeable."{{sfn|Daggett|1926|p=270}} He did, and president [[Raymond Poincar<U+00E9>]] noticed a change in Clemenceau's attitude towards Romania after Marie's arrival. After staying in Paris for a week, Marie accepted George V and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]'s invitation and crossed the [[English Channel]], lodging at [[Buckingham Palace]]. Hoping to acquire as much goodwill for Romania as possible, Marie became acquainted with many important political figures of the time, including [[George Curzon, 1st Marquess Curzon of Kedleston|Lord Curzon]], [[Winston Churchill]] and Waldorf and [[Nancy Astor, Viscountess Astor|Nancy Astor]]. She also frequently visited her son Nicky, who was then in school at [[Eton College]].{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=282<U+2013>83}} Marie was elated to have returned to England after so much time, writing that "it was a tremendous emotion to arrive in London, and to be greeted at the station by George and May."{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=280}}

After the end of her visit in England, Marie returned to Paris, where the people were just as excited for her arrival as they had been a few weeks before. Crowds gathered around her frequently, waiting to see the "exotic" Queen of Romania. American President [[Woodrow Wilson]] remained unimpressed by Marie, and her comments on Russian laws dealing with sexual relations, which were considered inappropriate, did not help.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=282<U+2013>83}} Marie shocked many officials by waving all her ministers aside and leading negotiations herself. On this, she would later comment, "Never mind, you'll all just have to get used to accepting me with the faults of my virtues."{{sfn|Daggett|1926|p=282}} Marie left Paris with numerous supplies for Romania's relief and later that year, the conference [[Treaty of Versailles|resulted]] in the international recognition of Greater Romania, thus doubling Ferdinand and Marie's kingdom to {{convert|295000|km2|sqmi}} and increasing the population by ten million.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=282<U+2013>83}} This led [[Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna of Russia (1890<U+2013>1958)|Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna of Russia]], who briefly lived in Bucharest, to conclude that "by her charm, beauty, and ready wit, [Marie] could obtain anything she desired".{{sfn|Maria Pavlovna|1932|p=16}}

=== Dynastic efforts ===
[[File:Constantin Pascali - Regina Maria.jpg|thumb|upright|Marie as queen, early 1920s]]

In 1920, Marie's eldest daughter, Princess Elisabeth, was engaged to [[George II of Greece|Prince George of Greece]], the eldest son of the deposed King of the Hellenes, [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine I]] and of Sophia of Prussia (formerly the Duchess of Sparta). After inviting George and his two sisters, the [[Helen of Greece and Denmark|Princesses Helen]] and [[Princess Irene, Duchess of Aosta|Irene]], to lodge with them at Sinaia, Marie organised numerous activities for the young couple and was delighted at the prospect of marrying off her daughter, whose character was severely flawed. In October, reports of [[Alexander of Greece|King Alexander]]'s death came from Greece; the Greek princesses needed to be returned to their parents as soon as possible. The following day, news arrived that Marie's mother had died in her sleep in [[Zurich]].{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=297}} Marie made arrangements for her departure to Switzerland, where she would take Helen and Irene to their parents and arrange her mother's funeral. Meanwhile, George and Elisabeth would remain at Sinaia.{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=305}}

Soon enough, Crown Prince Carol proposed to Princess Helen and they were married the following year. Marie was delighted, as she had frowned upon Carol's relationship with [[Zizi Lambrino]] and had been worried at the birth of their illegitimate son, [[Carol Lambrino|Carol Mircea]], who, to her great relief, had been given his mother's surname;{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=274<U+2013>78}} the child was considered illegitimate and spent most of his life trying to prove otherwise. In 1922, Marie married her second daughter, "Mignon", to [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander I of Serbia]] (later of Yugoslavia). She was delighted at the births of her two royal grandsons, [[Michael of Romania|Prince Michael of Romania]] (b. 1921) and [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Prince Peter of Yugoslavia]] (1923<U+2013>1970); the births of two children destined to sit on Europe's thrones seemed to cement her ambitions. Marie's dynastic efforts were viewed by critics as those of a manipulative mother who would sacrifice her children's happiness in order to fulfil her ambitions; in reality, Marie never forced any of her children to marry without their full consent.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=308}}

In 1924, Ferdinand and Marie undertook a diplomatic tour of France, Switzerland, Belgium and the United Kingdom. In England, she was warmly welcomed by George V, who declared that "apart from the common aims, which we pursue, there are other and dear ties between us. Her Majesty the Queen, my dear cousin, is British born."{{sfn|Mandache|2011|pp=152<U+2013>53}} Similarly, Marie wrote that the day of her arrival in England was "a great day for me, one of emotions, sweet, happy and the same time glorious emotions to come back as Queen to my own country, to be received officially, in all honour and enthusiastically into the bargain <U+2013> to feel your heart swell with pride and satisfaction, to feel your heart beat and tears start into your eyes, while something gave you a lump into your throat!"{{sfn|Mandache|2011|pp=152<U+2013>53}} These state visits were a symbolic recognition of the prestige Romania had gained after World War I. Whilst visiting [[Geneva]], Marie and Ferdinand became the first monarchs to enter the newly established headquarters of the [[League of Nations]].{{sfn|Mandache|2011|pp=152<U+2013>53}}

=== Coronation ===
[[File:Marie Coronation portrait.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Marie's official coronation portrait]]

The location for Marie and Ferdinand's coronation as sovereigns of Greater Romania was [[Alba Iulia]], which had been an important fortress in the Middle Ages and where [[Michael the Brave]] had been declared ''[[Voivode]]'' of Transylvania in 1599, thus uniting Wallachia and Transylvania for the first time.{{sfn|Elsberry|1972|p=178}} An Orthodox cathedral was built as the [[Coronation Cathedral, Alba Iulia|Coronation Cathedral]] in 1921.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Yt1M3egMbWMC&pg=PA236&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=236|title=Transylvania|author=Lucy Mallows|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|date= 19 Mar 2013}}</ref>  An elaborate set of jewellery and clothing was made especially for the coronation. Marie's crown was designed by painter [[Costin Petrescu (painter)|Costin Petrescu]] and it was made in the [[Art Nouveau]] style by "Falize", a Parisian jewelry house. The crown was inspired by that of Despina, the wife of 16th-century Wallachian ruler [[Neagoe Basarab]], and it was made entirely out of Transylvanian gold. The crown had two pendants on the sides; one contained an image of the royal arms of Romania and the other, the arms of the Duke of Edinburgh, which Marie had used as her own arms prior to her marriage. The crown, which cost around 65,000 [[French franc|franc]]s, was paid for by the state, via a special law.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Coroana reginei Maria | author=Ilie, Cornel Constantin | journal=Istorie <U+0219>i Civiliza<U+021B>ie |date=November 2011 | volume=3 | issue=26 | page=78 | issn=2066-9429 }}</ref>

Among the guests at the royal couple's coronation were Marie's sister "Baby Bee", the [[George VI|Duke of York]] and French generals [[Maxime Weygand]] and [[Henri Mathias Berthelot]]. The ceremony was conducted by the [[Patriarch of All Romania|Metropolitan of All Romania]], [[Miron Cristea]], but it was not performed inside the cathedral as Ferdinand, a Roman Catholic, refused to be crowned by a member of the Eastern Orthodox Church. After placing his crown on his own head, Ferdinand crowned Marie, who had knelt before him. Immediately, cannons were fired as a sign that the first monarchs of Greater Romania had been anointed. A feast was given in the same room where the union had been proclaimed in 1918; there, more than 20,000 peasants were offered roast steaks. The following day, Ferdinand and Marie triumphantly entered Bucharest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jurnalul.ro/campaniile-jurnalul/recurs-la-romania/incoronarea-regilor-romaniei-desavarsite-110633.html | title=<U+00CE>ncoronarea Regilor Rom<U+00E2>niei Des<U+0103>v<U+0103>r<U+0219>ite | work=Jurnalul Na<U+021B>ional | date=1 December 2007 | accessdate=7 December 2013 | author=Anghel, Costin | language=Romanian }}</ref> The splendour of the coronation was subsequently cited as evidence of Marie's theatricality.{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=318}} Marie would be received into the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] in 1926, mentioning a desire to be closer to her people.<ref name="ciobanu">{{cite web | url=http://jurnalul.ro/special-jurnalul/regina-maria-povestea-vietii-mele-568017.html | title= Regina Maria: Povestea vie<U+0163>ii mele | work=Jurnalul Na<U+021B>ional | date=10 February 2011 | accessdate=17 December 2013 | last1=Anghel |first1=Carmen |last2=Ciobanu |first2=Lumini<U+021B>a | language=Romanian }}</ref>

=== Visit to America ===
{{Quote box
 | quote  = Not even the pelting rain and mist that obscured the distant Statue of Liberty could dim the royal welcome that greeted Queen Marie of Roumania as she landed at the Battery Park this morning.
 | source = <U+2014> ''[[The Montreal Gazette]]'', a Canadian newspaper<ref>{{cite news | title=The Queen of Roumania arrives in America | work=The Montreal Gazette | date=20 October 1926 | accessdate=7 December 2013 | location=Montreal | page=3}}</ref>
 | width  = 25em
 | align  =right
}}

The [[Maryhill Museum of Art]] in [[Maryhill, Washington]] was initially designed as a mansion for wealthy businessman [[Samuel Hill]]. However, at [[Loie Fuller]]'s behest, the building was turned into a museum instead. Hill wished it to be dedicated in 1926, and he conceived it as a monument to peace, to his wife Mary, and to Queen Marie herself. Marie agreed to come to America and witness the dedication, especially as Fuller was an old friend of hers. Fuller quickly put together a committee that supported Marie's "tour" of America and arrangements were made for her departure.{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=341}} Marie viewed the tour as an opportunity to "see the country, meet the people and put Romania on the map".{{sfn|Elsberry|1972|p=196}} She travelled by ship across the Atlantic Ocean and disembarked in New York, on 18 October 1926, accompanied by Prince Nicholas and Princess Ileana.

{| class="toccolours" style="float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 35%;" cellspacing="5"
| style="text-align: left;" |
Oh, life is a glorious cycle of song,<br />
A medley of extemporanea;<br />
And love is a thing that can never go wrong;<br />
And I am Marie of Roumania.
|-
| style="text-align: left;" | <small>[[Dorothy Parker]], 1927<ref>{{cite book | editor1-last=Rawson |editor1-first=Hugh | editor2-last=Miner |editor2-first=Margaret |year=2006 |title= The Oxford Dictionary of American Quotations |location=New York |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn= 978-0-19-516823-5 }}</ref></small>
|}

Upon her arrival, Marie was welcomed enthusiastically by the American people, with "whistle of steamers, roar of guns in white smoke puffs against gray fog, voices cheering in a stinging rain". She was formally greeted by [[Jimmy Walker]], the serving [[Mayor of New York City]].{{sfn|Morris|1927|p=13}} Constance Lily Morris, author of ''On Tour with Queen Marie'', wrote that the people were excited for Marie's arrival mainly because of her almost mythical allure, which had been created by papers and rumour throughout her life; she observed that "the modest [[Elisabeth of Bavaria, Queen of Belgium|Queen of the Belgians]]  had once come with [[Albert I of Belgium|her king]] for a brief visit and years ago the dusky [[Kal<U+0101>kaua|Hawaiian ruler]] had honored us, but there had been no others. The time could not have been better set." Marie was also fairly popular within [[suffragette]] circles, where she was viewed as "a woman whose wits had devised many a coup d'<U+00E9>tat, whose brains had thought out many a difficult problem for her people, who had used the gifts given her to further every good purpose".{{sfn|Morris|1927|pp=18<U+2013>19}}

During their time in America, Marie, Nicholas and Ileana undertook tours of several cities, including [[Philadelphia]]. They were very popular, and were greeted with equal enthusiasm in each city they visited, so much so that "[Nicholas and Ileana] seemed fairly dazed by their tremendous ovation".{{sfn|Morris|1927|p=29}} Before leaving the United States, Marie was presented with a bullet-proof armored town car by [[Willys-Knight]], which she joyfully accepted. On 24 November, Marie and her children were seen off by a delegation from [[Washington, D.C.]], as they prepared to leave by ship from [[New York Harbour]]. Morris wrote that "our last view was of Her Majesty, her children on either side, waving back with that tear-and-smile of those who pass from happy scenes."{{sfn|Morris|1927|p=232}} Morris accompanied the queen throughout her journey and offered a very detailed account of Marie's time in America in her book, published in 1927.

Marie was delighted with the visit, and wished to return to America as soon as possible. She wrote in her diaries:{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=327}}
<blockquote>
"both my children and I have but one dream: to return! To return to that stupendous New World, which makes you almost guiddy {{sic}} because of its immencity, {{sic}} its noise, its striving, its fearful impetuous {{sic}} to get on, to do always more, always bigger, quicker, more astonishingly a restless, flaring great world, where I think everything can be realised&nbsp;... I know, as long as I live, breathe and think, the love for America will beautify my life and thoughts&nbsp;... Perhaps Fate will allow me one day to go back to America."
</blockquote>

== Widowhood (1927<U+2013>38) ==

=== 1927<U+2013>30 ===
[[File:Queens Marie and Helen with King Michael.jpg|thumb|left|Marie with Helen and Michael, 1927<U+2013>30]]

Prince Carol sparked [[Romanian dynastic crisis|a dynastic crisis]] when he officially renounced his rights to succeed Ferdinand on 5 January 1926, simultaneously waiving all parental rights over Prince Michael, who had been proclaimed heir. A Provisional Regency Bill was passed, creating a regency council composed of Prince Nicholas; the Orthodox Patriarch, [[Miron Cristea]]; and [[Gheorghe Buzdugan]], the president of the [[High Court of Cassation and Justice|Court of Cassation]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Reununciation of Prince Charles | work=The Age | date=6 January 1926 | accessdate=11 December 2013 | location=Melbourne, Vic. | page=5}}</ref> However, both Marie and Ferdinand were reluctant to leave the country in the hands of a five-year-old boy, even overseen by a regency, for fear that the lands gained during World War I would be reclaimed by neighbouring countries and that political disturbances might lead to civil unrest. Nevertheless, when Marie returned from America, Ferdinand's death seemed imminent. He was suffering from [[intestinal cancer]], and by April 1927 had come so close to death as to be given the last rites of the Catholic Church. He died on 20 July, in Marie's arms. She later wrote: "'I am so tired' were his last words and when he lay so quiet in my arms one hour later, I knew that I must thank God for ''him'' at least. This was rest indeed."{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=327<U+2013>28}}

Michael automatically succeeded as king upon Ferdinand's death and the regency council took charge of his role as monarch. In May 1928, Carol, who had found his life abroad with [[Magda Lupescu]] unsatisfactory,{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=327}} attempted to return to Romania with the help of the [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|1st Viscount Rothermere]]. He was prevented from doing so by English authorities, who then proceeded to expel him from England. Infuriated, Marie sent an official apology to George V on behalf of her son, who had already begun plotting a coup d'<U+00E9>tat.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=329<U+2013>30}} Carol succeeded in divorcing Princess Helen on 21 June 1928, on grounds of incompatibility.<ref>{{cite book | title=Helen, Queen Mother of Rumania, Princess of Greece and Denmark: An Authorized Biography | publisher=Faber and Faber | author=Lee, Arthur Gould | year=1956 | location=London | page=121 | oclc=1485467 }}</ref>

Marie's popularity was severely affected during Michael's reign and, after refusing to be part of the regency council in 1929, she was accused by the press, and even by Princess Helen, of plotting a coup.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=332}} During this time, there were numerous rumours as to Princess Ileana's marriage. After talk of Ileana marrying the [[Boris III of Bulgaria|Tsar of Bulgaria]] or the [[Alfonso, Prince of Asturias (1907<U+2013>1938)|Prince of Asturias]],{{sfn|Mandache|2011|p=152}} she was eventually betrothed to [[Alexander Hochberg|Alexander, Count of Hochberg]], a minor German prince, in early 1930.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Ileana Engaged | journal=The Outlook |date=February 1930 | volume=134 | issue=7 | pages=257<U+2013>58}}</ref> This betrothal was, however, short-lived and Marie never managed to conclude a political marriage for her youngest daughter, instead marrying her to the Italian-born [[Archduke Anton of Austria|Archduke Anton of Austria<U+2013>Tuscany]] in 1931.{{sfn|Mandache|2011|p=152}}

=== Carol's reign ===
[[File:Philip Alexius de Laszlo-Queen Marie of Romania, nee Princess Marie of Edinburgh.jpg|thumb|right|Marie in 1936, by [[Philip de L<U+00E1>szl<U+00F3>]]]]

On 6 June 1930, Carol arrived in Bucharest and made his way into Parliament, where the Act of Succession 1927 was duly declared null. Thus, Carol usurped the throne from his son, becoming King Carol II. Upon hearing of Carol's return, Marie, who was abroad, was relieved. She had been growing anxious with the direction in which the country was heading and viewed Carol's return as the [[Parable of the Prodigal Son|return of the Prodigal Son]]. However, as soon as she arrived in Bucharest, she became aware that things would not go well. Carol refused to accept his mother's advice to take Helen back{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=332}} and never sought Marie's counsel during his reign, thus making the already existing breach between mother and son complete.{{sfn|Easterman|1942|pp=86<U+2013>87}}

Desolate and almost stripped of her belief, Marie turned to the religious teachings of the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith]], which she found "vastly appealing".{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=337}} Marie was the first member of a royal family to become a Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>.<ref>{{cite journal | title=100 Years of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith in Europe | author=Hassel, Graham; Fazel, Seena | journal=Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Studies Review | year=1998 | volume=8 | pages=35<U+2013>44}}</ref> She later wrote:<ref>{{cite book | title=The World Order of Baha'u'llah. Selected Letters | publisher=Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Publishing Trust | author=Effendi, Shoghi | authorlink=Shoghi Effendi | year=1991 | location=Wilmette, Ill. | page=93 | isbn=0-87743-231-7}}</ref> 
<blockquote>
"The Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teaching brings peace and understanding. It is like a wide embrace gathering together all those who have long searched for words of hope. It accepts all great Prophets gone before, it destroys no other creeds and leaves all doors open. Saddened by the continual strife amongst believers of many confessions and wearied of their intolerance towards each other, I discovered in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teaching the real spirit of Christ so often denied and misunderstood: Unity instead of strife, Hope instead of condemnation, Love instead of hate, and a great reassurance for all men."
</blockquote>

In 1931, Prince Nicholas eloped with Ioana Doletti, a divorced woman. Marie strongly disapproved of her son's actions and felt hurt by Doletti's repeated attempts to keep Nicholas from communicating with his mother. Although she blamed the women in her sons' lives for a while, she also came to blame herself, for failing to educate them properly. However, she stubbornly and continually refused to meet Magda Lupescu, even after Carol's pleas. Until her last years, Marie seldom even mentioned Lupescu's name.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=350<U+2013>52}}

With Carol's mistress hated throughout the country, it was only a matter of time before opposition to the King emerged. This opposition most prominently came under the form of the [[Iron Guard]], a group supported by [[Benito Mussolini]] and [[Adolf Hitler]]. After Carol turned to Ion Duca for help, the Iron Guard assassinated Duca in December 1933.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=350<U+2013>52}} After Duca's death, Carol's popularity plummeted and there were rumours that an attempt would be made on his life at the annual independence parade. In order to avoid this, he instead had Marie attend the parade, in what would be her final public appearance.{{sfn|Elsberry|1972|p=253}}

After the parade, Carol set out to destroy his mother's popularity among Romanians and tried to push her out of the country. Marie, however, did not comply, instead retreating to either of two locales.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=352}} The first was [[Bran Castle]]. Located near [[Bra<U+0219>ov]] in southern Transylvania and given to her as a gift in 1920 by grateful local officials, she had it restored over the next seven years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.historia.ro/exclusiv_web/destinatii-istorice/articol/castelul-bran-istorie-mit | title= Castelul Bran, de la istorie la mit | publisher=historia.ro | work=Historia Magazine | accessdate=18 December 2013 | author=Alexandra, Radu}}</ref> The other was Balchik, where she had built [[Balchik Palace|a palace]] and a small chapel called ''Stella Maris'' and tended to her garden. She also visited Ileana and her children in Austria. Ileana rarely received permission from Carol to visit Romania; this irritated Marie greatly. She also spent some time in [[Belgrade]] with her daughter "Mignon" and her son-in-law, King Alexander. In 1934, Marie visited England once again,{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=352}} meeting the [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Duchess of York]], by whom she was enchanted.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Queen Mother and Her Century | publisher=Dundurn | author=Bousfield, Arthur; Toffoli, Garry | year=2002 | location=Toronto | page=49 | isbn=1-55002-391-8}}</ref>

=== Illness and death ===
[[File:BisericaEpiscopalaCurteaDeArges (12).JPG|thumb|left|Marie's tomb in Curtea de Arge<U+0219> Monastery]]

During the summer of 1937, Marie fell ill.<ref name="odnb" /> Her personal physician, Dr. Castellani, determined she had [[pancreatic cancer]], although her official diagnosis was [[cirrhosis of the liver]]. Marie had not been a drinker and, upon hearing the news, she reportedly said: "then there must be a non-alcoholic cirrhosis of the liver, because I have never in my life tasted alcohol."{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=363}} She was prescribed a diet of cold foods, injections and bed rest. Marie was so weak at times that she could not even pick up a pen. In February 1938, she was sent to a sanatorium in Italy, in hopes that she might recover. There, she was visited by Nicholas and his wife, whom Marie eventually forgave for her transgressions. She was also visited by Princess Helen, whom she had not seen in nearly seven years, and Waldorf Astor. Marie was eventually transferred to a sanatorium in [[Dresden]]. Growing weaker and weaker, she requested that she be taken back to Romania, in order to die there. Carol denied her a journey by aeroplane,{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=363<U+2013>64}} and she declined a [[Air medical services|medical flight]] offered by Hitler,<ref name="hitler">{{cite web | url=http://www.historia.ro/exclusiv_web/portret/articol/iubirile-reginei-maria | title= Iubirile reginei Maria | publisher=historia.ro | work=Historia Magazine | accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> instead choosing to return to Romania by train. She was brought to Peli<U+0219>or Castle.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=363<U+2013>64}}{{#tag:ref|According to official reports, in keeping with [[Carol II of Romania's cult of personality|Carol's cult of personality]], Marie was still alive upon reaching the castle. However, she may in fact have died while on the train, in the [[Bac<U+0103>u]] area. At the time, another rumour suggested that Carol had fired a gun at Nicolae, the bullet hitting Marie when she threw herself before the latter.<ref name="hitler"/>|group=note}}

Marie died on 18 July 1938, at 5:38 p.m., eight minutes after lapsing into a coma.{{sfn|Pakula|1984|p=418}} Her two eldest children, Carol and Elisabeth, accompanied by Prince Michael, were at her deathbed.{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=363<U+2013>64}} Two days later, on 20 July, Marie's body was brought to Bucharest, where she [[Lying in state|lay in state]] in the white drawing room at Cotroceni Palace. Her coffin was surrounded by flowers and glowing tapers and was guarded by officers of the Fourth Hussars. Thousands of people filed by Marie's bier during the three-day lying in state and, on the third day, the palace was opened for factory workers. Marie's funeral cortege made its way to [[Bucharest North railway station|the train station]], passing under the [[Arcul de Triumf|Arch of Triumph]]. Her coffin was taken to [[Curtea de Arge<U+0219> Monastery]], where she was interred. Marie's heart, according to her own wishes, was placed in small golden casket embellished with the emblems of the [[Historical regions of Romania|Romanian provinces]] and interred in her ''Stella Maris'' chapel in Balchik. In 1940, after Southern Dobrudja was [[Treaty of Craiova|ceded to Bulgaria]] during [[World War II]], her heart was transferred to Bran Castle.{{sfn|Pakula|1984|pp=418<U+2013>20}} There, Ileana built a chapel to house the heart, kept in two nested boxes placed inside a marble sarcophagus.<ref name="inima">{{cite web |url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/ploiesti/foto-video-inima-reginei-maria-vine-peles-decorul-atmosfera-palatului-balcic-1_51910ba5053c7dd83f953f85/index.html | title=Inima reginei Maria vine la Pele<U+015F>, <U+00EE>n decorul <U+015F>i atmosfera palatului de la Balcic | work=Adev<U+0103>rul | date=13 May 2013 | accessdate=17 December 2013 | author=Mihai, Dana | language=Romanian }}</ref>

Marie was the last Queen consort of Romania, as Princess Helen was only ever awarded the title of Queen Mother between 1940 and 1947. She was one of Queen Victoria's five reigning granddaughters and one of three to retain their position as consort after the conclusion of World War I, alongside the [[Maud of Wales|Queens of Norway]] and [[Victoria Eugenie of Battenberg|of Spain]].

== Legacy ==

According to one of her biographers, Diana Mandache, Marie published 34 books and short stories, both in Romanian and English, during her lifetime.{{sfn|Mandache|2011}} This included her critically acclaimed autobiography, ''The Story of My Life'', published by Cassell in London, in three volumes. The book was reviewed by [[Virginia Woolf]], who felt it was too familiarizing of the royal family. She stated that "suppose that among the autumn books of 2034 is ''Prometheus Unbound'', by George the Sixth, or ''Wuthering Heights'', by Elizabeth the Second, what will be the effect upon their loyal subjects? Will the British Empire survive? Will Buckingham Palace look as solid then as it does now? Words are dangerous things, let us remember. A republic might be brought into being by a poem."<ref>{{cite book | title=Women and Writing | publisher=Harcourt, Inc. | author=Woolf, Virginia | authorlink=Virginia Woolf | year=1979 | location=New York | page=198 | isbn=0-15-193775-3  | ignore-isbn-error=true}}</ref> Marie kept a diary from December 1918 until shortly before her death, and the first volume was published in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.romlit.ro/jurnalul_reginei_maria | title= Jurnalul Reginei Maria | work= Rom<U+00E2>nia literar<U+0103> | date=13 October 2004 | accessdate=19 December 2013 | author= S<U+0103>ndulescu, Al. | language=Romanian }}</ref>

[[File:Medal - Marie of Romania.jpg|thumb|upright|A medal depicting Marie]]

Even before her ascension as queen, Marie had succeeded in establishing her public image as that of "one of the best-looking and richest princesses in Europe".<ref>{{cite book | title=The Three Emperors | publisher=Fig Tree | author=Carter, Miranda | year=2009 | location=London | page=124 | isbn=978-0-670-91556-9}}</ref> She was known primarily for her talent in horse-riding, writing, painting, sculpting, dancing and for her beauty.<ref>{{cite book | title=Queen Victoria and the Discovery of the Riviera | publisher=Tauris | author=Nelson, Michael | year=2007 | location=London | page=127 | isbn=978-1-84511-345-2}}</ref> Her popularity was dimmed by two slanderous campaigns: that conducted by the Central Powers during World War I;{{sfn|Duca|1981|p=153}} and that led by communist officials after Romania's transition to a [[Socialist Republic of Romania|Socialist Republic]] in 1947.

During Romania's 42 years under communist rule, Marie was alternately depicted as either an "agent of English capitalism" or as a devoted patriot who believed that her destiny was intertwined with that of Romania. In the 1949 ''Adev<U+0103>rata istorie a unei monarhii'' ("The True History of a Monarchy"), author Alexandru G<U+00E2>rnea<U+021B><U+0103> refers to orgies that supposedly were held by Marie at Cotroceni and Balchik and claims that, in fact, her cirrhosis was caused by her heavy drinking, even offering examples of instances when a drunken Marie needed to be carried out of a yacht by her fellow drinkers. Marie's supposed extramarital affairs were brought forward as evidence of promiscuity, which contravened communist values.<ref name="lupsor"/> In 1968, communist officials vandalised the chapel sheltering Marie's heart, opening the sarcophagus and taking the boxes as well as the heart into Bran Castle. In 1971, these were transferred to Bucharest's [[National Museum of Romanian History]].<ref name="inima"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://adevarul.ro/cultura/istorie/75-ani-moartea-reginei-maria-1_51e6f606c7b855ff564bb7a5/index.html | title=75 de ani de la moartea Reginei Maria | work=Adev<U+0103>rul | date=18 July 2013 | accessdate=18 December 2013 | author=Mandache, Diana | language=Romanian }}</ref> It was not until the late period of [[Nicolae Ceau<U+0219>escu]]'s regime, the last years before the [[Romanian Revolution]], that Marie's merits came to be acknowledged.<ref name="lupsor">{{cite web | url=http://www.historia.ro/exclusiv_web/portret/articol/regina-maria-critica-i-laude-istoriografia-comunista | title=Regina Maria, <U+00EE>ntre critic<U+0103> <U+0219>i laude <U+00EE>n istoriografia comunist<U+0103> | publisher=historia.ro | work=Historia Magazine | accessdate=16 December 2013 | author=Lup<U+015F>or, Andreea}}</ref>

In Romania, Marie is known by the nickname "Mama R<U+0103>ni<U+021B>ilor" (Mother of the Wounded),<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.romanialibera.ro/cultura/aldine/cine-este-regina-care-a-devenit-mama-ranitilor-296852.html | title=Cine este regina care a devenit 'mama r<U+0103>ni<U+021B>ilor' | publisher=Rom<U+00E2>nia Liber<U+0103> | date=5 November 2012 | accessdate=26 November 2013 | author=P<U+0103>durean, Claudiu}}</ref> or simply as "Regina Maria", while in other countries she is remembered as the "Soldier Queen" and "Mamma Regina".<ref>{{cite news | title=Queen thinks Rumania will Battle Again | work=St. Petersburg Daily Times | date=4 October 1918 | accessdate=16 December 2013 | page=4}}</ref>{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|pp=273<U+2013>74}} Marie is also nicknamed "the mother-in-law of the Balkans", due to her children's marriages among ruling houses in the Balkans. By the time of her death, Marie's children had ruled in three of the four Balkan countries, Bulgaria excepted,{{sfn|Gelardi|2005|p=308}}{{sfn|Mandache|2011|p=151}} although her descendants no longer occupy any European throne. Marie was called "one of the greatest figures in Romanian history" by [[Constantin Argetoianu]],<ref>{{cite book | title=Pentru cei de m<U+00E2>ine: Amintiri din vremea celor de ieri | publisher=Humanitas | author=Argetoianu, Constantin | authorlink=Constantin Argetoianu | language=Romanian | year=1992 | location=Bucharest | page=109 | isbn=978-973-28-0224-3}}</ref> and in her memory, the Order of the Cross of Queen Marie was established in Romania.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.medal-medaille.com/product_info.php?products_id=10283 | title=Order of the Cross of Queen Marie | publisher=medal-medaille.com | accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.medals.org.uk/romania/kingdom-romania/kingdom-romania031.htm | title=Kingdom of Romania: Order of the Queen Marie Cross | publisher=medals.org.uk | accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>

Prior to 2009, many of Marie's personal belongings were on display at Bran Castle, her residence in her later years, which functions as a museum.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bran-castle.com/royal-residence.html | title=Royal Residence | publisher=bran-castle.com | work=Bran Castle | accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> That year, when the castle was legally restored to Princess Ileana's heirs, the [[Ministry of Culture and National Patrimony|Culture Ministry]] moved the collection of her items to a nearby building, ''Vama Medieval<U+0103>'', which is also open to visitors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.romanialibera.ro/actualitate/eveniment/colectiile-din-castelul-bran-mutate-la-vama-medievala-148964.html | title= Colec<U+021B>iile din Castelul Bran, mutate la Vama Medieval<U+0103> | publisher=Rom<U+00E2>nia Liber<U+0103> | date=17 March 2009 | accessdate=30 March 2014| language=Romanian}}</ref> The Maryhill Museum of Art holds a permanent exhibition titled "Marie, Queen of Romania"; this display includes the queen's coronation gown, a copy of the crown, silverware, gilt furniture and jewelry, among other items.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/oradea/foto-coroana-reginei-maria-atras-sute-vizitatori-1_50aebbd27c42d5a6639fb2f7/index.html | title= Coroana Reginei Maria a atras sute de vizitatori | publisher=Adev<U+0103>rul | date=15 October 2012 | accessdate=30 March 2014| author=Barbu, Florina | language=Romanian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.maryhillmuseum.org/2013/visit/exhibitions/ongoing-exhibitions/queen-marie-of-romania | title=Marie, Queen of Romania | publisher=maryhillmuseum.org | work=Maryhill Museum of Art | accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>

